shared_text:
Sweet Owen Day Fall Festival
September 8 at 3:18 PM ·

It is with thoughtful consideration and deep regret that we announce Sweet Owen Day 2020 will be canceled. After much discussion, the planning committee decided to not host the 2020 festival due to COVID-19. We believe that the health and safety of our community is our top priority. We strongly believe, in light of the current situation, canceling the event is the responsible thing to do. We recognize that our decision will have an impact on our community but we assure you we did not come to this decision lightly.

Sponsorships are a large part of making Sweet Owen Day a success. We could not in good consciousness ask sponsors to invest money in these difficult times. Thank you to each of the sponsors that have contributed through the years to make Sweet Owen Day a success.

We look forward to coming back bigger, better and stronger on September 18, 2021.

Respectfully,
Sweet Owen Day Planning Committee
Owen County Chamber of Commerce

post_text: After reviewing the results of the online survey concerning Addiction Recovery Care’s (ARC) plans to locate to Owenton in early 2021, Owen County Judge/Executive Casey Ellis and Owenton Mayor Adam Gaines hosted a town-hall-style Zoom meeting with ARC on Wednesday, Sept. 2. In addition to answering many of your questions, ARC also provided in-depth background information on the organization and its mission. We hope this video will provide the information many of you have sought in recent months.

post_text: Owen County Judge/Executive Casey Ellis recently signed a proclamation declaring Wednesday, Aug. 26, 2020, Women’s Equality Day, commemorating the 100th anniversary of the adoption of the 19th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, which prohibits the states and the federal government from denying the right to vote to citizens of the U.S. based on sex. The proclamation was given to the John Guill-Polly Hawkins Craig Chapter of the Daughters of the American Revolution and will be displayed at the Owen County Public Library.

Owen County EMS
August 4 at 3:57 PM ·

Through the hard work of Owen County Emergency Services Pediatric Coordinator Paramedic Nicki Sullivan, OCEMS today acquired nearly 150 stuffed toys from major retailer Ty Inc. to be distributed to pediatric patients transported by the service.

Sullivan, along with members of her shift, filled several care bags with the stuffed toys (Beanie Babies), coloring books, crayons, and a temporary tattoo. The care bags will be placed on all front-line ambulances beginning today.

We appreciate Nicki and all EMS employees' dedication to our service and the community at large.

Pictured left to right: Ashley Tackett, Nicki Sullivan, Josh Riley, Deanna Tracy, and Travis Logan

post_text:
The U.S. Census Bureau began mailing postcards last week to those households which have not yet responded to the 2020 U.S. Census. The postcards serve as the final reminder that residents will receive.

The Bureau’s door-to-door operations will begin Aug. 11, with sworn enumerators, appropriately masked and gloved, visiting residences that have not completed their census. This operation will run through Oct. 31, according to U.S. Census Bureau Partnership Specialist Erin Peabody.

Owen County’s response rate currently stands at 53%, an improvement from the final self-response rate in 2010 of 51%. Despite the improvement, we are still ranked 99th in total self-response out of 120 counties in the state.

If you have not already, please take 10 minutes to visit 2020census.gov or call 844-330-2020 to respond today! Our community is counting on you.

post_text:
An update regarding the event held at the Owen County Fairgrounds Saturday, July 25, 2020:

Top Dog Promotions hosted a demolition derby at the fairgrounds on Saturday, July 25.

Saturday’s event was not sanctioned or supported by Owen County Government. The event was discouraged by the Three Rivers District Health Department, according to a social media post made by a representative of the health department.

As COVID-19 cases continue to increase not just locally, but across Kentucky, it falls on each of us to do what we can to stop the spread of coronavirus by maintaining a distance of 6 feet from others, wearing face coverings indoors, wearing face coverings outside when unable to follow social-distancing, regular hand washing and hand sanitizing, cleaning and disinfecting surfaces, and staying home when you’re sick.

Kentucky American Water
July 1 at 7:49 PM ·

After nearly a year of construction, we officially celebrated the completion of our new $1.4 million field operations facility in Owenton. Owen County Judge Executive Casey Ellis and Owenton Mayor Adam Gaines joined us today for a safe, socially-distanced, ceremonial ribbon cutting at the new facility.

This investment will serve as an operational hub for our Northern Division, which includes Franklin, Gallatin, Grant and Owen counties. The 9,900-square-foot maintenance garage has nearly 6,600 square feet of garage space as well as 3,400 square feet for personnel needs.

To read more about this project, please visit: http://ow.ly/bChu50Anrsr

Photo by: J Kathryn Photography

post_text: These pictures represent the results of our first Free Dump Day after three months off due to COVID-19. At times, the line to get in was wrapped around Owenton First Baptist Church. We thank everyone for their patience as we believe this is the largest intake we've ever had in a single day and will likely take at least three or four days to clean up. As a reminder, Free Dump Day is held from 7:30 a.m.-3:30 p.m. on the last Saturday of each month unless otherwise noted. The event is open to Owen County residents only (you may be asked to show your ID). At this time, Commonwealth Cleanup Week and the Tire Amnesty Program remain postponed.

post_text: Through a partnership with the Owen County Family Resource and Youth Services Center, the Owen County Drug Prevention Coalition and Freestore Foodbank, approximately 400 families were provided with food yesterday, including produce, meat and dry goods. Volunteers from area churches, Meeting the Needs, the Owen County Judge-Executive's Office, Owen County Schools, Northern Kentucky Community Action and NKADD made sure the drive-thru event went off without a hitch. Thank you to the organizations that helped secure the food for our community during this unprecedented time.

post_text: On Monday, June 1, the UMC Food Ministry began its weekly delivery of meals to Owen County students. Deliveries will be made Monday-Thursday. If you were a car-rider during the 2019-2020 school year, you may pick up your food box from the exhibit hall at the Owen County Fairgrounds, 355 Ellis Road, Owenton, from 10 a.m.-noon, Monday-Friday. In addition to serving students, the ministry will also service those 18 and under who are not enrolled in the school system. For more information on receiving food, please contact UMC Food Ministry's central office at 859-261-4010.

post_text: Have you visited www.govoteky.com to request an absentee ("mail-in") ballot yet? It's simple and only takes a few moments. If you're unsure about voting absentee, take a look at the easy-to-follow instructions attached to this post. Remember, your absentee ballot must be postmarked on or before June 23, or deliver it to the Owen County Clerk's Office by 6 p.m., June 23. In-person voting at the clerk's office begins at 8 a.m., Monday, June 1. You may call the clerk's office at 502-462-7100 to schedule an appointment between the hours of 8 a.m.-4 p.m., Monday-Friday, until June 22. In-person voting will also be an option from 6 a.m.-6 p.m. on Election Day (June 23) at the Owen County Extension Office only.

Free Dump Day, Tire Amnesty Program and Commonwealth Cleanup Week remain postponed

The Owen County Transfer Station will not host "Free Dump Day" tomorrow, Saturday, May 30. Free Dump Day is typically held on the last Saturday of each month but is postponed for the foreseeable future due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic. The event normally draws a large crowd to the transfer station, and by delaying the event, we can ensure the safety of our public works employees during these unprecedented times. The Tire Amnesty Program and Commonwealth Cleanup Week also remain postponed.

For more information, please see the attached press release.

post_text: Did you know the first census was in 1790? Only 230 years ago! Under the U.S. Constitution, the very first responsibility of the federal government is a count of all persons living in the U.S. Taking the census is a civic duty, and impacts support for infrastructure, transportation planning, emergency preparedness, disaster relief, education funding, health tracking and disease control, as well as a multitude of other things. Be sure your household is counted in 2020 by visiting https://my2020census.gov/ or calling 844-330-2020 today!

post_text: Every 10 years, the U.S. Census Bureau undertakes a mammoth task: counting all the people residing in the U.S. This count affects the allocation of funding for our community’s public resources (e.g., roads, schools and libraries), how we plan for the future and our voice in government. This year, responding to the census is easier than ever, and your response can aid Owen County in receiving millions of dollars for essential services over the next 10 years. Visit https://my2020census.gov/ or call 844-330-2020 to respond today.

OWEN COUNTY TRANSFER STATION UPDATE

As part of Gov. Andy Beshear’s “Healthy at Work” initiative, the Owen County Transfer Station will resume normal operations beginning Monday, May 18, 2020, with the stipulation that ALL patrons MUST remain in their vehicles while at the attendant's station to maintain proper social-distancing guidelines.

The updated rates and policies — approved by the Owen County Fiscal Court Feb. 18 — will become effective once normal operations resume.

At this time, the monthly “free day," the Tire Amnesty Program and Commonwealth Cleanup Week remain postponed.

For questions, please call the Owen County Judge-Executive’s Office between 8 a.m.-4 p.m., Monday-Friday at 502-484-3405.

On Friday, May 8, Misty, Crosby, Fiona and myself, along with members of the local Complete Count Committee — Donette Gaines, Blair Baldwin, and Karen Wash — joined together at Owen County schools in an effort to further equip the community’s parents with information on the 2020 U.S. Census.

When families receive their meals today, they will find a flyer with details on responding to the Census if they have not already.

Census data guides how more than $675 billion in federal funding is distributed to states and communities each year for schools, health care facilities, roads, transportation, social services, and more.

By responding to the Census today, you can help ensure adequate funding for our school system to help our children receive the education needed to become the leaders of tomorrow.

Residents with P.O. boxes or renters that have recently moved may not have received their self-reporting form in the mail, but can still respond by visiting 2020census.gov or by calling 1-844-330-2020.

COVID-19 Update, Please Share.

April 22, 2020

We still have 0 confirmed COVID-19 cases in Owen County.

Governor Beshear announced 196 new cases today, bringing the state total to 3,373. The Governor also reported 14 additional deaths, bringing the total number of deaths to 185. The good news is the number who have recovered continues to grow faster, with the total now reaching 1,311.

Governor Beshear announced plans to ramp up testing to 20,000 tests per week beginning next week. With only 36,075 tests done to-date in Kentucky, this will be a drastic increase in testing.

The U.S. death toll has now risen to over 46,600, an increase of more than 2,400 deaths in the past 24 hours.

Please continue to follow the CDC guidelines and wear a face covering if you must go out for essentials.

Stay Safe, Stay Healthy and Stay Home.

#lovinOC
#HealthyAtHome
#TeamKentucky

I pray that God blesses each of you and your family with a safe and healthy Easter.

Stay Safe, Stay Healthy and Stay Home.

COVID-19 Update, Please Share

April 5, 2020

No changes to report this evening. We still have 0 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Owen County.

As I’ve said before, I have no doubt it’s here and you should always act as if it is. Governor Beshear reported more than 30 new positives today in this state. That statistic is a bit deceiving as he eluded to. Last Sunday’s report was 45 new cases which was sizably lower. That’s because a lot of labs aren’t reporting on Sunday or have less staff working running tests on this day. 5 more deaths have occurred in this state from COVID-19.

Please continue to practice social distancing and adhere to guidelines that will help you protect yourself and the ones you love.

Stay Safe and Healthy

Owen County Judge/Executive Casey Ellis
April 1 at 10:09 PM ·

Covid-19 Update

April 1, 2020

Good Evening,

More than 90 additional cases of COVID-19 in Kentucky were confirmed today. As of now, there are still 0 confirmed cases in Owen County. As I said this morning, we know this will not remain 0 forever and you should act as if it is here, because it is very very likely that it is.

Due to the fact that social distancing is not happening in certain businesses some changes were made today. A big thank you to Owenton Police Chief Terry Gentry for working with our Owenton & Owen County businesses to ensure compliance of the Social Distancing rules.

Stores are encouraged to enforce this and local law enforcement will also be assisting to ensure compliance.

Please look at the graph below, you can see the estimated lives saved by the practices the Governor has put into place. While it may not be an exact science, this model uses the best possible data from other countries and other states. Up to 30,000 lives verses 3000 by our arc estimates. This is huge!!!!

Stay safe, stay healthy and stay home if at all possible!

I am begging that each of you follow the proper guidelines and not put our families at any higher risk.

Stay home and if you must go out follow the guidelines below.

shared_text:
Owen County Judge/Executive Casey Ellis
March 20 at 10:35 AM ·

Press Release
Prescription Delivery Availability

To further prevent the spread of COVID-19 Cull Family Pharmacy is closing the inside of their store to the public. This will be in effect starting at 10 am today (3/20/20). Prescription medications will still be available for pick up. As before, they have made accommodations to bring prescriptions out to your car. Give them a call at 502-484-3046 to let them know you are here, and they will be happy to bring you your medicine.

In addition to Cull Pharmacy’s curbside pick up and delivery service, I have ordered Owen County Public Transit and Owen County EMS to help fulfill the delivery needs in support of Cull Pharmacy should the need arise. For your convenience, Cull Pharmacy will coordinate any delivery needs so there is no need to contact any other agency.

Casey Ellis
Owen County Judge/Executive

shared_text:
Owen County School Nutrition
March 13 at 6:28 PM ·

Meals will be delivered beginning March 16th!

To best serve all students School Nutrition, with the help of the Transportation Department, will plan to deliver breakfast and lunch meals to students by school bus. Buses will run their entire bus routes Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays during this closure period. Monday’s and Wednesday’s deliveries will consists of 2 breakfast meals and 2 lunch meals for each student at each bus stop. Friday’s delivery will consist of 1 breakfast meal and 1 lunch meal for each student.

For students who are car riders ONLY, you may pre-order meals by calling 502-484-4089 and leaving the student(s) name(s) on voicemail. The order must be requested no later than 4:00 PM on Monday for pickup on Tuesday and no later than 4:00 PM on Wednesday for pickup on Thursday. Those requested meals must be picked up on Tuesdays and Thursdays at the Owen County High School cafeteria side door (located next to the gym entrance) between the hours of 9:00 AM and 1:00 PM.

Owen County Schools
March 13 at 11:32 AM ·

Upon recommendation from Governor Beshear, Owen County Schools will transition to Non-Traditional Instruction (NTI) days beginning Monday, March 16th. As of now, regular classes will resume and students will report back to school after Spring Break on Monday, April 13th. During this period, students will not report to school and will receive instruction via online platforms and prepackaged teacher assignments. Please be aware this could change and NTI days, or school closure, could be extended based on further recommendations by Governor Beshear and state health agencies. Please see the official statement below from Dr. Robert Stafford for full details.

This count affects the allocation of funding to our communities public resources ; schools, roads, emergency services, public health agency, etc. , it determines our representation in the federal government and how our voices are heard. To learn more about the #2020Census and how to participate visit: 2020census.gov
